TY  - JOUR
T1  - Analysis of Profit-Linked Total-Factor Productivity Measurement Models at the Firm Level
AU  - Miller, David M.
AU  - Rao, P. Mohan
Y1  - 1989/06/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.35.6.757
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.35.6.757
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 757
EP  - 767
VL  - 35
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The purpose of the paper is to present the results of a comparative analysis of two main-line productivity measurement procedures: the American Productivity Center's total factor model, and the Ethyl Corporation's ?Profitability = Productivity + Price Recovery? model. Several fundamental differences between the two approaches are identified and analyzed. As demonstrated in the paper, differences such as the method of deflation can substantially affect the proper choice of the more appropriate procedure to use in a given corporate setting.
AB  - The purpose of the paper is to present the results of a comparative analysis of two main-line productivity measurement procedures: the American Productivity Center's total factor model, and the Ethyl Corporation's ?Profitability = Productivity + Price Recovery? model. Several fundamental differences between the two approaches are identified and analyzed. As demonstrated in the paper, differences such as the method of deflation can substantially affect the proper choice of the more appropriate procedure to use in a given corporate setting.
